{
  "texts": [
    "The downside is that the precise details of how the fine-tuning is accomplished is not available to the user.",
    "Furthermore, we observe a nonlinear trend in the fine-tuning time with respect to the dataset size and number of training epochs, indicating that the fine-tuning time likely depends on external (hidden) factors such as the number of other requests in the queue and the available computational resources.",
    "The other constraint in using the OpenAI interface is the cost, which is currently $25 USD per 1 million training tokens for the GPT-4o model and $3 USD per 1 million training tokens for GPT-4o-mini.",
    "Base models Llama-3-8B-Instruct 10 and Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct foot_10 were fine-tuned using QLoRA (loaded in 4-bit quantization for faster training) (Dettmers et al., 2024; Hu et al., 2021), with an adapter rank of 64 and a scaling factor of 16, for 5 epochs using a single T4 GPU foot_11 on two different sizes of training sets as shown in Table 9.",
    "The smallest of the Llama-3-family models requires only 2.2 GB of GPU RAM to be fine-tuned and can be trained on a small dataset in approximately 10 minutes."
  ]
}